metadata.name: Dancing Line ÁáïËàû #170
metadata.description:
This work is inspired by thinking about lines. Points, lines, and surfaces are the most basic elements of art. Whether or not an art work can be made using only lines and colors is a direction that has been explored recently. By connecting points at different distances, the color and transparency can produce different light and shade effects with the change of distance. In addition, a rotation algorithm is generated during the connection process, which can create light and shade, density, and the beauty of curves with relatively rich layers. , like a swallow dancing in the air is the resulting arc path. Hence the name Yanwu. Of course, another Chinese meaning of Yanwu is a brand of early Chinese TV sets, which also commemorates the era of creativity. I am also grateful to be able to contribute to the construction of Web3. There are 3 background colors, 7 line colors, and 30 dance times in this work, among which there are millions of combinations of point positions. This work only displays the background color, line color and dance times in the feature information.
Made With P5.js.
20% of royalties will be donated to the Processing Foundation.

metadata.name: Elevation #277
metadata.description:
There‚Äôs so much more to our world than what we are able to perceive, let alone understand. Will we ever be able to even fully understand ourselves?

‚Äì

Elevation is a series of 320 generative elevation drawings of imaginary structures. It is a reminder of the limits of our consciousness, and an ode to the manifold nuances that lie beyond what we can perceive, beyond what we even can imagine.

As a generative artist, I aim to elevate my own consciousness with the help of the machine. I welcome algorithms and randomness into the creation of my works, taking full control, and intentionally giving it away, always seeking to expand my imagination. For as humans alone, we remain limited to our own edifice of thought, and often fail to free ourselves from the visible, mundane world.

Both are present in Elevation: the visible and the imaginary, the mundane and the transcendent, the solid and the fragile. Where an architect‚Äôs elevation drawing marks the transition from the thought world into the visible world, Elevation remains in-between, depicting both the idea of an imaginary structure, and the structure itself.

‚Äì

Elevation is intended for print. All holders of an Elevation NFT will be able to order the corresponding signed print in the respective paper format via andreasrau.eu/elevation. Press [s] to save the image as displayed or [p] to generate a print-ready PNG image at 300 dpi. This might take a while, depending on paper format and your hardware.

‚Äì

Elevation
p5.js, glsl, html, css
Andreas Rau, 2022

metadata.name: Polyvalence #164
metadata.description:
Polyvalence is a collection of imaginary architectures.
Polyvalent architectures, parts, and blocks allow for multiple readings over time. In a mode of continuous reconfiguration, they reveal various tectonic interior and exterior spaces, creating an endless fuzzy whole. Each minted polyvalence token displays various deterministic rare features, layouts, styles, scales and is in constant reconfiguration, endlessly creating polyvalent imaginary architectures.     

Polyvalence Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2021

metadata.name: Geometry tumbler #128
metadata.description:
Some arbitrary geometric shapes that hover in place until interacted with.

Each click will animate each shape to a new randomised position (x, y, z), as well as play some hits from a selection of random scales.

The longer you hold your pointer down, the more tension builds, resulting in a more intense shape displacement as well as a faster playing speed on the tones.

Doing that for long enough will also trigger one out of two effects, either putting a sepia layer over the scene or encapsulating it with a darkened vignette. There‚Äôs about a 3% chance of not getting a ‚Äúhold-in effect‚Äù but instead getting your whole scene rendered with a chromatic aberration.

There are 2 different instruments to collect. A Berlin Concert Grand Piano and a Harmonised 3-Oscillator Pad.

There‚Äôs about a 3.2% chance of getting a spheric shape instead of a cubic shape.

In addition to all this, you can get various amounts of shape counts, and each one can have a different color theming as well as different metalness and roughness materials.

There‚Äôs also a plethora of different lightings to get such as ambient, point and spotlights in different color themes.

Finally there‚Äôs a percentage indicator that reflects the uniqueness of each shape composition down to a finer detail, taking all of these parameters in account.

@computeremotions - 2022-06-19

metadata.name: Arbour #13
metadata.description:
There is something almost subversive about generative art that mimics nature. Rather than excelling at abstract mathematical beauty, it tries to hold the complexity and elegance of the natural world, all while attempting to be interesting art. This makes it a different kind of challenge than the mathematical attractors and flow fields that are common across generative art.

It may be ironic then that the solution to natural forms is very often mathematical. The trees in this work are built recursively as a graph, much like how one could build a fractal. But chaos is mixed in at each step to allow the shapes to vary, and reduce their self-similarity. This is a different approach to L-systems but the results are very similar.

In this token, there are:
 - Three styles of tree.
 - Twelve colour schemes (six day, six night)
 - Four shapes for leaves.
 - Five leaf patterns
 - And other entropy that cannot be enumerated.

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #34
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. ‚ÄúThe Bugged Tree‚Äù‚Äôs code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren‚Äôt under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there‚Äôs a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan
